 But you also believe nuclear is fading out, so you want to also use natgas for 19 percent more, or a total of 58 percent?<br>
<br>
Nah, let's have solar take some of the slack, say 5 percent.  The over-night problems of solar will keep it from getting much higher than that, I firmly believe....<br>
<br>
So, natural gas is to provide 50 percent of our electricity, wind 20 percent, hydro 10 or so, solar 5 percent?  That's 85 percent, and efficiency should be able to cover that. <br>
<br>
Sounds doable! <br>
<br>
Now, how do you price this, and how do we grow in the future?  Also, how do we power cars?  Keep importing oil, or run them on natgas?<br>
<br>
Plus, we have to get the CO2 down.....<br>
<br>
Well, almost anything is better than coal.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, yales, is this a reasonable swag at how you'd like things to look, or am I in left field some more?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Also, what about the rest of the world?  I can't imagine this being anything but expensive.....  I could be wrong.<br>
<br>
Ok, how much efficiency can we expect to reap?  Can we maintain our current standard of living in the West, AND bring the rest of the world up to a comparable standard of living, without increasing energy use at all?<br>
<br>
It might be possible, but I have no idea how....    <br>
